Cell[TextData[{
 
 CounterBox["Section"],
 ".",
 
 CounterBox["Subsection"],
 ".",
 " ",
 "Background"
}], "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.647595716860656*^9, 3.647595720121035*^9}, 
   3.662129351258013*^9}],

Cell["\<\
A TES is a superconductor kept in its transition from its superconducting \
phase to the normal regime, where it loses its superconducting properties. \
Photons incident on the sensor heat it, causing its resistance to rise \
sharply and then slowly fall to superconducting levels as the heat \
dissipates. A current is run through the TES, and the change in resistance is \
captured by the voltage signal of a superconducting quantum interference \
device (SQUID) inductively coupled to the TES circuit.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.6475958737488503`*^9, 3.647595901360673*^9}, {
   3.650015740372243*^9, 3.6500157842275143`*^9}, {3.650015826675685*^9, 
   3.650015848035693*^9}, 3.662129351295035*^9, 3.667307666167407*^9}],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Several groups of TES signal waveforms are shown in Figure ",
 
 CounterBox["NumberedFigure", "FigBoulderWaveforms"],
 " (each graph shows the set of signals elicited by an ensemble of laser \
pulses with an average number of photons per pulse given by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   OverscriptBox["N", 
    StyleBox["-",
     FontSlant->"Italic"]], TraditionalForm]], "Math"],
 "). For ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox[
     OverscriptBox["N", "-"],
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "=", "4"}], TraditionalForm]], "Math"],
 ", one can clearly distinguish the different photon numbers and their \
relative frequencies; for higher numbers this is harder. Higher photon \
numbers create higher signal amplitudes, but at a certain point the TES \
saturates in the normal regime and additional photons change the signal \
maximum very little."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.647595929393694*^9, 3.6475959757877927`*^9}, 
   3.647596030605841*^9, {3.647600186488763*^9, 3.64760019004554*^9}, 
